{{Self-contradictory|article|about=the sizes of craters|date=January 2018}}
{{Earth_Impact_Database_world_map.svg|480px}}
{{GeoGroupTemplate}}
This list of [[impact crater]]s on [[Earth]] contains a selection of the 190 confirmed craters given in the [[Earth Impact Database]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.passc.net/EarthImpactDatabase/index.html |title=Earth Impact Database }}</ref> To keep the lists manageable, only the largest craters within a time period are included. The [[List of impact craters on Earth#All craters listed alphabetically|complete list]] is divided into separate articles by geographical region.

==Confirmed impact craters listed by size and age==
These features were caused by the collision of meteors (consisting of large fragments of asteroids) or [[comets]] (consisting of ice, dust particles and rocky fragments) with the Earth. For eroded or buried craters, the stated diameter typically refers to the best available estimate of the original [[rim (craters)|rim]] diameter, and may not correspond to present surface features. Time units are either in [[Year#SI prefix multipliers|thousands]] ('''ka''') or [[Year#SI prefix multipliers|millions]] ('''Ma''') of years.

===Young craters (10 ka or less)===
Less than ten thousand years old, and with a diameter of 0.1&nbsp;km (100 meters) or more. The EID lists only 7 or 8 such craters, and the largest in the last 100,000 years (100 ka) is the 4.5&nbsp;km [[Rio Cuarto craters|Rio Cuarto crater]] in [[Argentina]].<ref name=bland>Bland, Phil A.; de Souza Filho, C. R.; Timothy Jull, A. J.; Kelley, Simon P.; Hough, Robert Michael; Artemieva, N. A.; Pierazzo, E.; Coniglio, J.; Pinotti, Lucio; Evers, V.; Kearsley, Anton; (2002); [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/11367157_A_possible_tektite_strewn_field_in_the_Argentinian_Pampa_Science "A possible tektite strewn field in the Argentinian Pampa"], ''Science'', volume 296, issue 5570, pp. 1109-1112</ref> However, there is some uncertainty regarding its origins<ref name="rio">{{cite Earth Impact DB |name=Rio Cuarto |linkname=riocuarto |accessdate=2009-08-19 }}</ref> and age, with some sources giving it as < 10 [[kiloannum|ka]]<ref name="bland" /><ref name="schultz" /> while the EID gives a broader < 100 ka.<ref name="rio" />

The [[Kaali crater|Kaali impacts]] (c. 2000 BC) during the [[Iron Age]] may have influenced [[Estonian mythology#Mythical motifs in folklore|Estonian and Finnish mythology]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.folklore.ee/folklore/vol23/echoes.pdf |title=Echoes of Ancient Cataclysms in the Baltic Sea |accessdate=2008-10-26 |last=Haas |first=Ain |first2=Andres |last2=Peekna |first3=Robert E. |last3=Walker |publisher=Electronic Journal of Folklore }}</ref> the [[Campo del Cielo]] (c. 2000 BC) could be in the legends of some [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] tribes,<ref>{{cite web |title=Meteorites of Campo del Cielo: Impact on the indian culture |first=Giménez |last=Benítez |last2=López |first2=Alejandro M. |last3=Mammana |first3=Luis A. |url=http://www.fcaglp.unlp.edu.ar/~sixto/arqueo/w-6-ing.htm }}</ref><ref name="Bobrowsky">{{cite book |first=Peter T. |last=Bobrowsky |first2=Hans |last2=Rickman |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gpwgm022ltMC&pg=PA31 |pages=30–31 |title=Comet/asteroid impacts and human society: an interdisciplinary approach |publisher=Springer |year=2007 |isbn=3-540-32709-6 }}</ref> while [[Henbury crater|Henbury]] (c. 2200 BC) has figured in [[Aboriginal Australians|Australian Aboriginal]] oral traditions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Aboriginal oral traditions of Australian impact craters |first1=Duane W. |last1=Hamacher |first2=John |last2=Goldsmith |url=http://www.narit.or.th/en/files/2013JAHHvol16/2013JAHH...16..295H.pdf }}</ref>

