==={{anchor|Largest craters}} Largest craters (10 Ma or more)===
Craters with a diameter of 20&nbsp;km or more are all older than 10 Ma, with the exception of [[Karakul (Tajikistan)|Karakul]] (52 km) and the newly-discovered [[Hiawatha Glacier|Hiawatha crater]] (31 km, but not yet in the [[Earth Impact Database|EID]]) whose ages are uncertain. 

There are more than forty craters of such size. The largest two within the last hundred million years have been linked to two extinction events: [[Chicxulub crater|Chicxulub]] for the [[Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event|Cretaceous–Paleogene]] and the [[Popigai crater|Popigai impact]] for the [[Eocene–Oligocene extinction event]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Russia's Popigai Meteor Crash Linked to Mass Extinction |url=http://www.livescience.com/46312-popigai-crater-linked-eocene-mass-extinction.html |date=13 June 2014 }}</ref>
