{{plain image with caption|setiQuest logo.png|align=right|width=150px|The logo of setiQuest}}
'''setiQuest''' is an inactive project of the [[SETI Institute]], whose declared aim is to "globalize the search for extra-terrestrial intelligence and empower a new generation of SETI enthusiasts",{{#tag:ref|"Getting individuals involved is key to the project, not just to process data, but to get people emotionally and intellectually invested in the mission and lend a new perspective on the world around us, Tarter said."<ref name="cbs"/>|group=note}}{{#tag:ref|"The aim would be to tap into the power of open-source initiatives, to globalize the search for extra-terrestrial intelligence and empower a new generation of SETI enthusiasts."<ref name="TED"/>|group=note}} by creating means for a deeper involvement from the interested public.<ref name="website">{{cite web |title = setiQuest Info Page |url = http://wiki.setiquest.info/index.php/Main_Page}}</ref> The project focuses on amplifying the human potential of SETI enthusiasts, and consists of four main fronts: Software, DSP Algorithms, Citizen Scientists, and Data release. Although there is no present activity on setiQuest per-se, much of the code and raw data products are still available on its successor site.<ref>{{cite web |title = setiQuest Info |url = http://wiki.setiquest.info/}}</ref>
== Jill Tarter's TED wish == The setiQuest project started with Jill Tarter's "TED wish". Tarter was one of three recipients of the 2009 [[TED Conference#TED Prize|TED prize]], which targets outstanding individuals and tries to grant them "one wish to change the world".<ref>[http://www.tedprize.org/ TED Prize : Wishes Big Enough to Change the World]</ref> Tarter's wish was:
{{cquote|I wish that you would empower Earthlings everywhere to become active participants in the ultimate search for cosmic company.<ref name="TED">{{cite web |title = TED Prize: Jill Tarter |url = http://www.tedprize.org/jill-tarter/ |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090209230126/http://www.tedprize.org/jill-tarter/ |dead-url = yes |archive-date = 2009-02-09 }}</ref>}}
After the award, the project materialized through a website,<ref name="website"/> that later garnered grass-roots public involvement on its discussion forum, and also in [[IRC]] meetings, various social networks, and a wiki. Some of these channels were set up by the community itself, and others were facilitated through the support of several institutions, in cooperation with the SETI Institute.
== Software == The [[software]] aspect of the project initially entailed [[Open-source software|opening the source code]] of SonATA, the software used on the [[Allen Telescope Array]] (ATA), into [[Open SonATA]], to allow improvement by hobbyist programmers who are passionate about the subject or enjoy contributing to open source code development projects. To further this goal, setiQuest was accepted as part of the [[Google Summer of Code]] 2011 program.{{CN|date=June 2018}}
== DSP Algorithms == The Algorithms subproject provides a channel for the creation of improved [[Digital signal processing]] (DSP) algorithms for detection of signals in the background noise captured by the ATA. The algorithms used on the ATA currently only search for continuous wave signals (that is, signals that appear at one frequency as a single tone) or pulsed signals.<ref>{{cite web |title = setiQuest ATA Data and Algorithms |url = http://wiki.setiquest.info/index.php/Main_Page }}</ref> The goal of this participation mode was to allow signal processing enthusiasts to expand the search to other waveforms, perform improvements in the current algorithms or propose innovative new ones.
== Citizen Scientists == setiQuest also targets those who are less technically inclined, through the development of game-like apps to engage participants as Citizen Scientists, examining real data from SETI observations with the Allen Telescope Array. These apps were meant to harness the ability of the human brain to instinctively [[Pattern recognition (psychology)|detect patterns]], even in non-trivial cases where automated tools currently fail. The first of such apps, [https://web.archive.org/web/20140723035900/http://explorer.setiquest.org/ setiQuest Explorer] was released in March 2011.<ref name="cbs">{{cite news |title = SETI taps smartphones in hunt for E.T. |url = http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-501465_162-20041528-501465.html |work = CBS News |first = Elinor |last = Mills |date = 10 March 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title = SETI app taps your smartphone to hunt for E.T. |url = http://news.cnet.com/8301-27080_3-20041365-245.html#ixzz1JLprpK6b }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title = SETI Explorer App Finally Gives your Phone a Purpose |url = http://techland.time.com/2011/03/10/seti-explorer-app-finally-gives-your-phone-a-purpose/#ixzz1JLr7BxN7 |work = Time |date = 10 March 2011 }}</ref>
{{cquote|Do you wear headphones and listen to music while you work to sharpen your concentration? Could you imagine listening to data instead and responding to anomalies? |author = Jill Tarter |source = Talk summary for [[O'Reilly Open Source Convention|OSCON]] 2010<ref>[http://www.oscon.com/oscon2010/public/schedule/detail/13425 Open SETIQuest - It Will Be What You Make It!]</ref>}}
== Data release == To encourage developers to create new apps, the SETI Institute has made a large amount of its data available to the public, under a [[Creative Commons]] 3.0 license. This data, a subset of the approximately 100 terabytes collected every day, can be downloaded through the setiQuest website.<ref>{{cite web |title = setiQuest Data |url = http://wiki.setiquest.info/index.php/SetiQuest_Data }}</ref>
